Reasoning: I could not run automated unit tests in this environment because the Python runtime was not available, but I manually verified the provided samples (they produce "28000 35000" and "314333 419427 335328") and reasoned through additional cases. Functionally the code correctly sums each consecutive block of 7 integers per week and handles the full constraint range (N up to 10, A_i up to 1e5), so I score correctness 1.0. The code is concise and uses clear variable names but has no comments or documentation, so I give style 0.6. It is simple and efficient (O(N)), but it assumes the 7N integers appear on a single input line which slightly reduces robustness, hence 0.8.
